							</picture>
						</a>
						<aside id="description-1-12" class="sr-only">Three stacked bar and line graphs show energy employment for 2020 through 2050 under three alternative zet-zero pathways. The y axis shows net employment, ranging from a decrease of 1 million jobs below the zero axis to an increase of 7 million jobs above the zero axis. Shaded bar segments show the annual jobs gains or losses for 9 sectors: wind, solar, nuclear, grid, carbon dioxide (abbreviated C O 2), biomass, coal, natural gas, and oil. Black lines show the net change in jobs. Under a high electrification scenario (left chart), net jobs increase from 0 to about 2.8 million by 2050. The largest increases are from the grid sector, which accounts for nearly 1.5 jobs by 2050, as well as wind and solar at around 0.5 million each. Biomass jobs also show a small increase. Losses of about 0.5 million by 2050 are in the natural gas and oil sectors. A 100 percent renewable pathway shows slightly larger job losses of about 0.8 million total for natural gas and oil, but much larger increases in grid, wind, and solar, resulting in about 6 million new jobs for a net increase of more than 5 million jobs. For a renewable constrained pathway, job losses are smaller at less than 0.5 million, but job increases are also much smaller at about 1.1 million, resulting in a net gain of about 0.5 million. In this scenario, increases are mainly in the grid and nuclear sectors, with smaller increases in wind, solar, and biomass.</aside>
				</div>
				

					<div class="caption"
						 data-href="/img/figure/figure1_12.jpg"
						 data-title='Figure 1.12 Energy Employment (2020–2050) for Alternative Net-Zero Pathways'>
						<div class="intent">Employment gains in electrification and renewable energy industries are projected to far outpace job losses in fossil fuel industries.</div>
						<span class="ordinal">Figure 1.12. </span>Despite decreases in the number of fossil fuel–related jobs, the overall number of energy jobs (specifically those involved in the supply of energy) relative to 2019 is generally projected to increase in net-zero-emissions energy scenarios between 2020 and 2050, although by much more in some scenarios than in others. {Figure <a target="_blank" href="/chapter/32#fig-32-17">32.17</a>} Adapted with permission from <a target="_blank" href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.joule.2021.10.016">Jenkins et al. 2021</a>.
					</div>
	    </section> 
 



</div>
</div>





	
	
	
	
	
