g levels. No shading is used here, as the bars instead represent ranges of projections, and projections are for three warming levels: 2.7 degrees Fahrenheit, 3.6 degrees, and a range of 5.4 to 9 degrees. The current value is shown as about 5 inches. Future changes are about 18 to 35 inches, about 20 to about 37 inches, and about 24 to about 69 inches, respectively. The last bar has an asterisk indicating that the rise at the upper end of this range cannot be ruled out due to the possibility of rapid ice sheet loss. The amount of warming required to trigger such loss is not currently known but is assessed to be above 3.6 degrees Fahrenheit. The bottom right chart shows the number of coastal flooding events per year, with projections for the same three warming levels as in the sea level rise chart. Text notes that sea level rise drives an increase in the number of major coastal flooding events per year due to high tides alone. Current values are from 0.05 to 0.1. Future values are about 3, about 5, and about 182 events, respectively. 182 events per year translates into every other day. " readonly/>
